Introduction

Hello! This is a Fitness Tracker data analysis project I am doing for the Capstone project module as part of my Google Data Analytics certification. In this case study, I will perform many real-world tasks of a data analyst. I will imagine I am working for a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products like a smart watch or a fitness band for men & women, and meet different team members. In order to answer the key business questions, I will follow the steps of the data analysis process: ask, prepare, process, analyze, share and act.

By the end of this project, I will have hopefully demonstrated to you with this case study some of the skills I’ve acquired through my certification.

Scenario

I am a Data Analyst working on the marketing analyst team. The high-tech manufaturer is a successful company but they have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. The co-founder & chief creative officer believes that analyzing smart device fittness data could help unlock new growth opportunities for the company. I have been asked to focus on one of the products and analyze smart device data to gain insight into how consumers are using their devices. The insights you discover will then help guide marketing strategy for the company.

Phase 1: Ask

The goal of this phase is to identify a clear statement of business task and consider key stakeholders.

1.1 Goal

The goal is to identify how consumers use smart devices and apply insights into the company’s marketing strategy to improve consumer health.

1.2 Stakeholders

The final presentation will be given to the following stakeholders:

  1. Co-founders
  2. Chief Creative Officer
  3. Member of the executive team
  4. Director of Marketing

Phase 2: Prepare

The goal of this phase is to identify the data sets we need to use for our analysis. Verify the privacy, accessibility and security concerns with this data.

2.1 Datasets

The datasets used for this case study is FitBit Fitness Tracker data. This dataset is stored on Kaggle. This data set contains personal fitness tracker from thirty consumers.

2.2 Accassibility & Privacy

Verifying the metadata of our dataset confirms it is open-source. The owner has dedicated the work to the public domain by waiving all of his/her rights to the work worldwide under copyright law, including all related and neighboring rights, to the extent allowed by law. We can copy, modify, distribute and perform the work, even for commercial purposes, all without asking permission.

2.3 Data Generation

These datasets were generated by respondents to a distributed survey. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Variation between output represents use of different types of Fitbit trackers and individual tracking behaviors/preferences.

2.4 Data Verification & Organization

There are 16 CSV files available to us. Each document represents different quantitative data tracked by Fitbit. The data is considered large, so each subject will have data in multiple rows. Every user has a unique ID and data in different rows since data is tracked by day and time. I was able to verify attributes and observations of each table. I counted sample size of each table and verified the length of survey analysis ~ 30 days.

2.5 Data Integrity

Due to the limitation of size (30 users) and lack of any demographic information there could be sampling bias. I are unsure if the sample is representative of the population as a whole. Another problem identified is that the dataset is not current and also has the time limitation of the survey.

Phase 3: Process

The goal of this phase is to identify the tool being used, verify data is clean i.e. free of errors, correctly formatted & ready for analysis and document the cleaning process.

The dailysleep_total dataset seem to have few duplicate entries. Let’s remove these, drop any NA values and then clean and standardize column names with clean_names() function. This function changes all characters to lowercase, replaces space with underscore, removes any special characters like %, *, - etc.and adds a suffix for duplicate column names for better uniformity and clarity.

dailysleep_total <- clean_names(dailysleep_total) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct()
dailysteps_total <- clean_names(dailysteps_total) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct()
dailyActivity_total <- clean_names(dailyActivity_total) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct()
hourly_steps <- clean_names(hourly_steps) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct()

We see that our column names are all lower case and separated by ’_’, we also have no NA or duplicate entries. ### 3.6 Formatting Data Now that our dataset is clean, let’s format date-time columns into the correct class as we will be merging some datasets later.

dailyActivity_total <- dailyActivity_total %>%
  rename(date = activity_date) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date, format= "%m/%d/%y"))
dailysteps_total <- dailysteps_total %>% 
  rename(date = activity_day) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date, format= "%m/%d/%y"))
dailysleep_total <- dailysleep_total %>% 
  rename(date = sleep_day) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date, format= "%m/%d/%y"))
hourly_steps <- hourly_steps %>% 
  rename(date_time = activity_hour) %>% 
  mutate(date_time = mdy_hms(date_time))

We successfully changed the class and standardized the column names. Let’s quickly verify this with head() function that shows top few rows.

4.2 Analysis

Let’s calculate daily averages from this dataset grouped by id. We will use summarise() function.

daily_avg <- dailyActivity_total %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise(mean_daily_steps = mean(total_steps), mean_daily_sleep = mean(total_minutes_asleep), mean_daily_calories = mean(calories))

Now that we have the daily averages, let’s classify our users into different activity level buckets since we have relevant data to classify them. We can classify them as follows:

  1. Not active: <4000 steps
  2. Lightly active: 4000 - 7000 steps
  3. Fairly active: 7000 - 10000 steps
  4. Very active: 10000+ steps
user_level <- daily_avg %>%
  mutate(user_level = case_when(
    mean_daily_steps < 4000 ~ "Not active",
    mean_daily_steps >= 4000 & mean_daily_steps < 7000 ~ "Lightly active", 
    mean_daily_steps >= 7000 & mean_daily_steps < 10000 ~ "Fairly active", 
    mean_daily_steps >= 10000 ~ "Very active"
  ))

user_level_percent <- user_level %>%

  summarise(cat_total= n()) %>% 
  mutate(percent = cat_total / sum(cat_total)) %>%

weekday_steps_sleep <- dailyActivity_total %>%

                          levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", 
                                     "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) %>%

Phase 5: Share

The goal of this phase is to visualize all the pattersn and relationships we’ve calculated and see what emerges from it. This can then be shared with non-technical folks for understanding and readability.

5.1 Visualization

Let’s start our visualization with hourly activity grouped by time. We will use ggplot2() package to perform this step.

hourly_steps %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarize(avg_steps = mean(step_total, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x=time, y = avg_steps, fill = avg_steps)) + 
  labs(title = "Hourly Steps in a Day", x = "Time of Day", y = "Average Steps") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "#32CD32", high = "#FF4500") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1000, by = 100))

ggarrange(
  ggplot(weekday_steps_sleep, aes(weekday, daily_steps)) +
    geom_col(fill = "#9BBB59") +
    labs(title = "Daily steps per weekday", x = "Weekday", y = "Daily Steps") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 10000, by = 2000)),
  ggplot(weekday_steps_sleep, aes(weekday, daily_sleep_hrs)) +
    geom_col(fill = "#4F81BD") +
    labs(title = "Hours asleep per weekday", x = "Weekday", y = "Daily Sleep in hrs") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
  )

With this, we can deduce some conclusions as below:

  1. Users are active most between 11am - 2pm and 6pm - 8pm, possibly because it’s lunchtime and after work hours where people have time to workout
  2. Users are active most days during the week except Sunday
  3. Users are sleeping ~ 7 hours every day meaning users are not sleeping the recommended 8hrs

Next, let’s visualize any correlation between these daily steps, saily sleep & calories burned and see what’s happening.

ggarrange(
  ggplot(dailyActivity_total, aes(x=total_steps, y=total_minutes_asleep/60)) +
    geom_jitter() +
    geom_smooth(color = "#FF6347") + 
    labs(title = "Daily steps vs Hours Asleep", x = "Daily steps", y= "Hours Asleep") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 12, by= 2)) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 18000, by= 4000)),
  ggplot(dailyActivity_total, aes(x=total_steps, y=calories))+
    geom_jitter() +
    geom_smooth(color = "#FF6347") + 
    labs(title = "Daily steps vs Calories", x = "Daily steps", y= "Calories") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Here we notice the following:

  1. There seems to be no relation between hours asleep and daily steps taken in a day because more asleep does not equate to more steps taken or vice-versa
  2. There is a positive correlation between daily steps taken and calories burned which makes sense as more steps burn more calories

Since we know that users are only sleeping ~ 7 hours during a weekday, lets visualize users not asleep

ggplot(dailyActivity_total, aes(x= time_not_asleep)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5,color= "#8B0000", fill = "#FFCCCB") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 340, by = 20)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Time in Bed Not Asleep", x = "Time in Minutes", y = "Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

From the histogram we see that users are not asleep but still in bed from 10 - 30 minutes on average. I think we have some interesting data-points & visualizations from which we can draw some insightful conclusions that we can share with the stakeholders in the next phase.

Phase 6: Act

The goal of the last phase is to utilize the analysis and visualizations done above and share some actionable insights to meet business goals.

6.1 Recommendations

The goal of this section is to provide high level recommendations to the stakeholders identified earlier based on the analysis done and patterns recognized.

Recommendations Description
Notification to user in bed When user is in bed, we can either send notifications early in the night alerting user to start winding down so they can sleep better and for recommended 8hrs or we can notify user when they wake up to start moving or exercise and utilize that time better when they are not asleep but still in bed. Users can also be shown a summary of the activities for that day to motivate users to get going.
Notification on move goals Notifications can be sent to user to reach a certain steps goal during the day sending catch up notifications before their bed time to motivate users to walk/run more. The positive correlation with calories directly results in improved health. These can be tailored to be sent when users are not very active like post lunch and early morning.
Reward System We can also attach some digital rewards to showcase user achievements. These rewards can be points or badges or both, rewarding everyday activity, goal completion, streak rewards, milestones achieved etc. This can definitely motivate many users to put in the extra effort.
Sleep summary and tracking To help users improve their sleep, we can show them a summary of their daily sleep with different datapoints like how often they woke up, snoring, sleep position, Time asleep etc. and then recommend apps/webpages to help improve. We can offer them weekly/monthly reports so they can see how their sleep is tracking and improving overtime.
More data will help The analysis is done on a relativily small dataset and will require much large amounts of data to improve the analysis further. There is also no distinction between the users age or gender which can further refine our findings. Hence, we recommend doing another round of data collection & prompt users to opt in to this feature voluntarily where we gather data over long periods of time from a variety of users.
